                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d303">
                <head>303. Special Memorandum Prepared by the Board of National Estimates, Central
                    Intelligence Agency<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d303fn1">Source: Johnson
                        Library, National Security File, Country File, Thailand, Vol. III, Memos,
                        4/65–12/65. Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">22–65</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1965-09-10">September 10, 1965</date>. </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>The Threat of Communist Subversion in Thailand</item>
                </list>
                <p rend="center">SUMMARY</p>
                <p>Thailandʼs chief vulnerability to Communist subversion lies in the northeast
                    region, which borders on Laos. The Chinese have recently increased <pb
                        facs="0692" n="650" xml:id="pg_650"/> their efforts to encourage dissidence
                    among poorly integrated minorities in this region, and the level of dissident
                    activity, although still very low, has risen somewhat. Bangkok is responding
                    with more vigorous security measures and efforts to remove economic grievances.
                    The chances are good that the government will be able to stay abreast of the
                    likely increase in Communist subversion. The outlook in Thailand would alter
                    greatly, however, if the Communists achieved definitive victory in Laos or South
                    Vietnam.</p>
                <p>[Here follows the body of the memorandum.]</p>
                <closer>For the Board of National Estimates: <lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="strong">Sherman Kent</hi>
                        </persName>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="italic">Chairman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
